node.text:
"Supernatural" and "Gilmore Girls" alum @jaredpadalecki and wife @genpadalecki purchased their current Austin home in 2012, and have spent the years since slowly creating their ideal modern farmhouse. That’s where their three children (Thomas, 9, Shepherd, 7, and Odette, 4), as well as numerous dogs, chickens, mini horses, and even bees, live together in harmony. The house—which began as a model “Texas Tuscan,” according to their designer, Virginia Davidson (@v_d_i_d)—underwent a full gut renovation in order to become a compound inspired by the historic German homesteads of nearby Fredericksburg.

Tour their whole home at our bio link. Photo by @michaelmuller7; design by @v_d_i_d; words by @rachwall_.

We're down in Austin, Texas, today visiting "Supernatural" star @jaredpadalecki and @genpadalecki as they take us through their cozy family home.

Watch the whole tour at our link in bio.

node.text:
“It feels period to start, and by the time you’re in the back, the house almost completely opens to the field,” homeowner David Ren says of the transition of his historic home in Hudson Valley.

Tour the renovated Victorian at our bio link. Photo by @matthewwilliamson; design by @workstead; styling by @mieketenhave; words by David Sokol.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 28, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
“It was really a beautiful spot right at the end of a row of all the new construction…[overlooking] the mountain,” interior designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) recalls of this Montana home, which is located at the Yellowstone Club in Big Sky. His clients, the Gravettes, with three young sons and two French bulldogs, were specifically in need of ample room for entertaining, as well as cozy spaces for their close-knit clan. “They wanted this to be somewhere they could all go,” Higgins adds.

Tour the mountainside home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by @ericrallen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 28, 2021. May be an image of nature, tree and grass.

node.text:
Bill Caleo, cofounder of the @thebrooklynhomecompany, a boutique real estate–development firm, and Megan Noetzel LeFauve, an interior designer, envisioned their Catskills home as a year-round compound for themselves, their children, and their extended families. In addition to the three-bedroom house, the property includes a garage with a bunk room, a guest cottage, a playhouse, a pool, and a pool pavilion. There’s even a pond full of sunfish, shiners, and bass.

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by Matthew Williams; design by @thebrooklynhomecompany and Megan Noetzel LeFauve; architecture by @langarchitecture; words by @stephen_wallis.

node.text:
“We felt like in New York we were getting the best of both cities in the gorgeous views,” designer @carolannblinken says, referring to the Manhattan location of her part-time residence. That home boasts breathtaking views across the Hudson River and into New Jersey. But as far as the eye may be able to see, Blinken has come even further when it comes to the creative process involved.

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by @jeffholt; design by @carolannblinken; words by @christianelemieux.

node.text:
“This is my entire apartment in New York, this one room,” @victoriassecret model @taylor_hill says of her Nashville home's closet, which features exposed beams and an antler chandelier. “I didn’t have enough closet space there, and here I am now with a whole room I’ve made into my closet.” The pink fabric chairs are a @chairish find, while the stained glass in the window is from Dealer’s Choice, a nearby auction house.

Explore her historic home at our bio link. Photo by @alyssarosenheck; styled by @alyssarosenheck; words by @libbycallaway1970.

node.text:
Enlisting the help of his longtime friend and frequent collaborator, interior designer @samuelamoia, @milliondollarlistingny star @stevexgold completely transformed the energy and flow of his expansive, well-lit loft in SoHo. “Steve has a very modernist aesthetic,” explains Amoia. “He wanted that to translate into the space without sacrificing all the great things about having a [SoHo] loft—high ceilings, exposed beams, and incredible windows.”

Tour his home exclusively at our link in bio. Photo by @nina.poon; design by @samuelamoia; words by @davidbryannash.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 27, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
The next time you walk through a friend’s home, do a quick visual sweep. Is it monochromatic, done in varying shades of beige, white, or blue? Houston-based interior designer Lucinda Loya (@lucindaloyainteriors) believes that once you’re aware, you’ll notice the ubiquity of uniformity. “You’ll start to see that a lot of projects lack contrast,” the decorator insists. “So I always put some black and some white in every room to provide a visual point of reference—from no color to absolute color. I call it the ‘equilibrium of interiors.’”

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by Gianni Franchellucci; design by @lucindaloyainteriors; words by @heidismitchell.

node.text:
“We loved the canopy of the 200-year-old native oaks right away, and the fact that the property was relatively small while still being zoned for two houses," says homeowner and designer Jessica Helgerson (@jhinteriordesign) of her Oregon property. "The little house was well sited and had good bones, so we kept the footprint and renovated it entirely.” On one side of the tiny house, the great room is home to the dining room and kitchen, which were furnished with vintage pieces of furniture. The walls are covered in wood cladding reclaimed from a barn on the property.

Tour the two homes on the property at our bio link. Photo by @aaronleitz; design by @jhinteriordesign and @yiannidoulis; words by @karinemonie.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 26, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
Brigette Lau wasn’t looking for a new house. But when a friend told her she’d seen an Atherton, California, place that reminded her of Lau, a female leader in the venture capital tech space, she had to take a look. Lau toured the 11,000-square-foot residence—a new, contemporary build by @pacificpeninsulagroup—and was sold thanks to the creek running across the property and its overall feeling of tranquility. “I loved it. There was so much foliage, not a lot of traffic,” she says. “It’s such a beautiful home.”

Tour the color-filled home at our bio link. Photo by @rogerdaviesphotography; design by @legaspicourtsdesign; words by @zoesessums.

node.text:
“[The owner] came to us and said, ‘I really want a glamorous bathroom,’” recalls @rushjenkins, the designer of this Wyoming home. “We wanted to make sure that there was not only this beautiful glam factor, but that there was also this connection to the natural environment.” Together with the owner, Jenkins and @klausbaer settled on these highly patterned slabs of marble with a color scheme reflective of the Wyoming landscape.

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @ericpiasecki; design by @wrjdesign; architecture by @berlin_architects; words by @jenniferleeflowers.
